Schema Document Properties

Target Namespace http://qifstandards.org/xsd/qif3
Version 3.0.0
Element and Attribute Namespaces
  • Global element and attribute declarations belong to this schema's target namespace.
  • By default, local element declarations belong to this schema's target namespace.
  • By default, local attribute declarations have no namespace.
Schema Composition
  • This schema includes components from the following schema document(s):
    • ../QIFLibrary/IntermediatesPMI.xsd
    • ../QIFLibrary/Topology.xsd
    • ../QIFLibrary/Geometry.xsd
Documentation The MeasurementResources.xsd schema file defines the global MeasurementResources element and specific types of MeasurementResources.

Declared Namespaces

Prefix Namespace
Default namespace http://qifstandards.org/xsd/qif3
xml http://www.w3.org/XML/1998/namespace
xs http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema
t http://qifstandards.org/xsd/qif3
Schema Component Representation
<xs:schema targetNamespace="http://qifstandards.org/xsd/qif3" elementFormDefault="qualified" attributeFormDefault="unqualified" version="3.0.0">
<xs:include schemaLocation="../QIFLibrary/IntermediatesPMI.xsd"/>
<xs:include schemaLocation="../QIFLibrary/Topology.xsd"/>
<xs:include schemaLocation="../QIFLibrary/Geometry.xsd"/>
...
</xs:schema>
top

Global Declarations

Element: AACMM

  • This element can be used wherever the following element is referenced:
    • CMM
Name AACMM
Type AACMMType
Nillable no
Abstract no
Documentation The global AACMM element gives information about an articulated arm coordinate measuring machine (AACMM).
XML Instance Representation
<AACMM
id="QIFIdType [1] ?">
<Name> xs:token </Name> [1] ?
<Description> xs:string </Description> [0..1] ?
<Manufacturer> xs:string </Manufacturer> [0..1] ?
<ModelNumber> xs:string </ModelNumber> [0..1] ?
<SerialNumber> xs:string </SerialNumber> [0..1] ?
<Mass> MassValueType </Mass> [0..1] ?
<Size> CartesianWorkingVolumeType </Size> [0..1] ?
Start Choice [0..1] ?
<LocationId> QIFReferenceType </LocationId> [1] ?
<Location> LocationType </Location> [1] ?
End Choice
<Attributes> ... </Attributes> [0..1] ?
<Calibrations> CalibrationsType </Calibrations> [0..1] ?
<EnvironmentalRange> EnvironmentalRangeType </EnvironmentalRange> [0..1] ?
<Resolution> ... </Resolution> [0..1] ?
<WorkingVolume> ... </WorkingVolume> [0..1] ?
<EffectiveWorkingVolume> ... </EffectiveWorkingVolume> [0..1] ?
<TemperatureCompensation> TemperatureCompensationType </TemperatureCompensation> [0..1] ?
<HomeLocation> PointType </HomeLocation> [0..1] ?
<NumberOfJoints> xs:int </NumberOfJoints> [0..1] ?
<MinMeasuringDistance> LinearValueType </MinMeasuringDistance> [0..1] ?
<MaxMeasuringDistance> LinearValueType </MaxMeasuringDistance> [0..1] ?
<ProbeTipDiameter> LinearValueType </ProbeTipDiameter> [0..1] ?
<Accuracies> AACMMAccuraciesType </Accuracies> [0..1] ?
</AACMM>
Schema Component Representation
<xs:element name="AACMM" type="AACMMType" substitutionGroup="CMM"/>
top

Element: AACMMAccuracyTest

  • The following elements can be used wherever this element is referenced:
    • AACMMB89Test
    • AACMMISO10360Test
    • AACMMPointAccuracyTest
Name AACMMAccuracyTest
Type CMMAccuracyTestBaseType
Nillable no
Abstract yes
Documentation The global AACMMAccuracyTest element is the head of a substitution group. Any element that is a member of the group may be substituted for the AACMMAccuracyTest element anywhere the AACMMAccuracyTest element may be used in an instance file.
XML Instance Representation
<AACMMAccuracyTest/>
Schema Component Representation
<xs:element name="AACMMAccuracyTest" type="CMMAccuracyTestBaseType" abstract="true"/>
top

Element: AACMMB89Test

  • This element can be used wherever the following element is referenced:
    • AACMMAccuracyTest
Name AACMMB89Test
Type AACMMB89TestType
Nillable no
Abstract no
Documentation The global AACMMB89Test element gives information about articulated arm CMM accuracy based on an articulated arm B89 CMM test.
XML Instance Representation
<AACMMB89Test>
<EffectiveDiameterPerformanceTest> EffectiveDiameterPerformanceTestType </EffectiveDiameterPerformanceTest> [0..1] ?
<SinglePointArticulationPerformanceTest> SinglePointArticulationPerformanceTestType </SinglePointArticulationPerformanceTest> [0..1] ?
<VolumetricPerformanceTest> VolumetricPerformanceTestType </VolumetricPerformanceTest> [0..1] ?
</AACMMB89Test>
Schema Component Representation
<xs:element name="AACMMB89Test" type="AACMMB89TestType" substitutionGroup="AACMMAccuracyTest"/>
top

Element: AACMMISO10360Test

  • This element can be used wherever the following element is referenced:
    • AACMMAccuracyTest
Name AACMMISO10360Test
Type ISO10360TestType
Nillable no
Abstract no
Documentation The global AACMMISO10360Test element gives information about articulated arm CMM accuracy based on an ISO10360 CMM test.
XML Instance Representation
<AACMMISO10360Test>
Start Choice [1]
<MaxErrorConstant> LinearValueType </MaxErrorConstant> [1] ?
<LinearError> LinearErrorType </LinearError> [1] ?
<LesserError> LesserErrorType </LesserError> [1] ?
End Choice
</AACMMISO10360Test>
Schema Component Representation
<xs:element name="AACMMISO10360Test" type="ISO10360TestType" substitutionGroup="AACMMAccuracyTest"/>

Element: AACMMPointAccuracyTest

  • This element can be used wherever the following element is referenced:
    • AACMMAccuracyTest
Name AACMMPointAccuracyTest
Type PointAccuracyTestType
Nillable no
Abstract no
Documentation The global AACMMPointAccuracyTest element gives articulated arm CMM accuracy as the maximum deviation of a measured point location from its actual location throughout the articulated arm CMM's working volume.
XML Instance Representation
<AACMMPointAccuracyTest>
<Accuracy> LinearValueType </Accuracy> [1] ?
</AACMMPointAccuracyTest>
Schema Component Representation
<xs:element name="AACMMPointAccuracyTest" type="PointAccuracyTestType" substitutionGroup="AACMMAccuracyTest"/>
top

Documentation The global WorkingClosedShellSet element gives information about a closed shell set. Each key in this element requires each item in a collection of items of the same type to have an id that is unique within the collection.
XML Instance Representation
<WorkingClosedShellSet>
<!--
Key Constraint - ShellsPointSetIdKey
Selector - t:PointSet/t:Point
Field(s) - @id
-->
<!--

Selector - t:Curve13Set/t:*
Field(s) - @id
-->

Key Constraint - ShellsSurfaceSetIdKey
Selector - t:SurfaceSet/t:*
Field(s) - @id
-->
<!--

Selector - t:VertexSet/t:Vertex
Field(s) - @id
-->
<!--

Selector - t:EdgeSet/t:Edge
Field(s) - @id
-->

Selector - t:LoopSet/t:Loop
Field(s) - @id
-->

Selector - t:FaceSet/t:Face
Field(s) - @id
-->

Element: WorkingVolume

  • The following elements can be used wherever this element is referenced:
    • ClosedShellSetWorkingVolume
    • CartesianWorkingVolume
    • SphericalWorkingVolume
    • CylindricalWorkingVolume
    • UserDefinedWorkingVolume
Name WorkingVolume
Type WorkingVolumeBaseType
Nillable no
Abstract yes
Documentation The global WorkingVolume element is the head of a substitution group. Any element that is a member of the group may be substituted for the WorkingVolume element anywhere the WorkingVolume element may be used in an instance file.
XML Instance Representation
<WorkingVolume/>
Schema Component Representation
<xs:element name="WorkingVolume" type="WorkingVolumeBaseType" abstract="true"/>

Complex Type: AngularErrorType

Super-types: None
Sub-types: None
Name AngularErrorType
Abstract no
Documentation The AngularErrorType defines a maximum angular error that increases linearly with the distance from measuring angle. To compute the error, add the BaseError to the ErrorRate times the distance from angle being measured. The units for angle being measured must be the same as those of the BaseError (This type of error is common in laser trackers).
XML Instance Representation
<...>
<BaseError> AngularValueType </BaseError> [1] ?
<ErrorRate> xs:decimal </ErrorRate> [1] ?
</...>
Schema Component Representation

<xs:element name="ErrorRate" type="xs:decimal"/>
</xs:sequence>
</xs:complexType>

Complex Type: SinglePointArticulationPerformanceTestType

Super-types: None
Sub-types: None
Name SinglePointArticulationPerformanceTestType
Abstract no
Documentation In this test, for each of three points, the location of the point is measured ten times. One point (the near point) is at 20% or less arm extension, one point (the far point) is at 80% or more arm extension, and one point (the middle point) is chosen so that the arm is only moderately extended. Then the maximum deviation of each position from the average position and also twice the standard deviation of the residuals are reported for each of the three points. This test is given in ASME AmericanNationalStandard B89.4.22-2004.
XML Instance Representation
<...>
<MaxDeviationFromAverageNear> LinearValueType </MaxDeviationFromAverageNear> [1] ?
<MaxDeviationFromAverageFar> LinearValueType </MaxDeviationFromAverageFar> [1] ?
<MaxDeviationFromAverageMiddle> LinearValueType </MaxDeviationFromAverageMiddle> [1] ?
<TwiceStandardDeviationNear> LinearValueType </TwiceStandardDeviationNear> [1] ?
<TwiceStandardDeviationFar> LinearValueType </TwiceStandardDeviationFar> [1] ?
<TwiceStandardDeviationMiddle> LinearValueType </TwiceStandardDeviationMiddle> [1] ?
</...>
Schema Component Representation
<xs:complexType name="SinglePointArticulationPerformanceTestType">
<xs:sequence>
<xs:element name="MaxDeviationFromAverageNear" type="LinearValueType"/>
<xs:element name="MaxDeviationFromAverageFar" type="LinearValueType"/>
<xs:element name="MaxDeviationFromAverageMiddle" type="LinearValueType"/>
<xs:element name="TwiceStandardDeviationNear" type="LinearValueType"/>
<xs:element name="TwiceStandardDeviationFar" type="LinearValueType"/>
<xs:element name="TwiceStandardDeviationMiddle" type="LinearValueType"/>
</xs:sequence>
</xs:complexType>

Simple Type: TemperatureCompensationEnumType

Sub-types: None
Name TemperatureCompensationEnumType
Content
  • Base XSD Type: NMTOKEN
  • value comes from list: {'NONE'|'DEVICE_ONLY'|'DEVICE_AND_PART_SAME'|'DEVICE_AND_PART_SEPARATE'}
Documentation The TemperatureCompensationEnumType enumerates values that describe types of temperature compensation. The DEVICE_AND_PART_SAME value means compensation is performed for both device temperature and part temperature, but the two temperatures are assumed to be the same. The DEVICE_AND_PART_SEPARATE value means temperature compensation is applied to both device and part, but the two temperatures are measured separately.
Schema Component Representation
<xs:simpleType name="TemperatureCompensationEnumType">
<xs:restriction base="xs:NMTOKEN">
<xs:enumeration value="NONE"/>
<xs:enumeration value="DEVICE_ONLY"/>
<xs:enumeration value="DEVICE_AND_PART_SAME"/>
<xs:enumeration value="DEVICE_AND_PART_SEPARATE"/>
</xs:restriction>
</xs:simpleType>

The XML Instance Representation table above shows the schema component's content as an XML instance.

  • The minimum and maximum occurrence of elements and attributes are provided in square brackets, e.g. [0..1].
  • Model group information are shown in gray, e.g. Start Choice ... End Choice.
  • For type derivations, the elements and attributes that have been added to or changed from the base type's content are shown in bold.
  • If an element/attribute has a fixed value, the fixed value is shown in green, e.g. country="Australia".
  • Otherwise, the type of the element/attribute is displayed.
    • If the element/attribute's type is in the schema, a link is provided to it.
    • For local simple type definitions, the constraints are displayed in angle brackets, e.g. <<pattern = [1-9][0-9]{3}>>.
  • If a local element/attribute has documentation, it will be displayed in a window that pops up when the question mark inside the attribute or next to the element is clicked, e.g. <postcode>.

Glossary

Abstract (Applies to complex type definitions and element declarations). An abstract element or complex type cannot used to validate an element instance. If there is a reference to an abstract element, only element declarations that can substitute the abstract element can be used to validate the instance. For references to abstract type definitions, only derived types can be used.

All Model Group Child elements can be provided in any order in instances. See: http://www.w3.org/TR/xmlschema-1/#element-all.

Choice Model Group Only one from the list of child elements and model groups can be provided in instances. See: http://www.w3.org/TR/xmlschema-1/#element-choice.

Collapse Whitespace Policy Replace tab, line feed, and carriage return characters with space character (Unicode character 32). Then, collapse contiguous sequences of space characters into single space character, and remove leading and trailing space characters.

Disallowed Substitutions (Applies to element declarations). If substitution is specified, then substitution group members cannot be used in place of the given element declaration to validate element instances. If derivation methods, e.g. extension, restriction, are specified, then the given element declaration will not validate element instances that have types derived from the element declaration's type using the specified derivation methods. Normally, element instances can override their declaration's type by specifying an xsi:type attribute.

Key Constraint Like Uniqueness Constraint, but additionally requires that the specified value(s) must be provided. See: http://www.w3.org/TR/xmlschema-1/#cIdentity-constraint_Definitions.

Key Reference Constraint Ensures that the specified value(s) must match value(s) from a Key Constraint or Uniqueness Constraint. See: http://www.w3.org/TR/xmlschema-1/#cIdentity-constraint_Definitions.

Model Group Groups together element content, specifying the order in which the element content can occur and the number of times the group of element content may be repeated. See: http://www.w3.org/TR/xmlschema-1/#Model_Groups.

Nillable (Applies to element declarations). If an element declaration is nillable, instances can use the xsi:nil attribute. The xsi:nil attribute is the boolean attribute, nil, from the http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance namespace. If an element instance has an xsi:nil attribute set to true, it can be left empty, even though its element declaration may have required content.

Notation A notation is used to identify the format of a piece of data. Values of elements and attributes that are of type, NOTATION, must come from the names of declared notations. See: http://www.w3.org/TR/xmlschema-1/#cNotation_Declarations.

Preserve Whitespace Policy Preserve whitespaces exactly as they appear in instances.

Prohibited Derivations (Applies to type definitions). Derivation methods that cannot be used to create sub-types from a given type definition.

Prohibited Substitutions (Applies to complex type definitions). Prevents sub-types that have been derived using the specified derivation methods from validating element instances in place of the given type definition.

Replace Whitespace Policy Replace tab, line feed, and carriage return characters with space character (Unicode character 32).

Sequence Model Group Child elements and model groups must be provided in the specified order in instances. See: http://www.w3.org/TR/xmlschema-1/#element-sequence.

Substitution Group Elements that are members of a substitution group can be used wherever the head element of the substitution group is referenced.

Substitution Group Exclusions (Applies to element declarations). Prohibits element declarations from nominating themselves as being able to substitute a given element declaration, if they have types that are derived from the original element's type using the specified derivation methods.

Target Namespace The target namespace identifies the namespace that components in this schema belongs to. If no target namespace is provided, then the schema components do not belong to any namespace.

Uniqueness Constraint Ensures uniqueness of an element/attribute value, or a combination of values, within a specified scope. See: http://www.w3.org/TR/xmlschema-1/#cIdentity-constraint_Definitions.
